					<head>Liturgy</head>
					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/n79090052" rend="visible">
						<summary>A festival prayer book with services for Rosh ha-Shanah, Yom Kipur and Sukot, according to the German rite.</summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he"/>
						<msItem n="0" rend="visible" class="lccn.loc.gov/n79090052">
							<locus from="1r" to="309v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Maḥzor </title>
							<title xml:lang="he">מחזור </title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="1r" to="27v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Services for the first day of Rosh ha-Shanah</title>
							<note>
								<p>Shaḥarit, folio 2r (only a small portion is preserved); tefilat musaf, folio 2v (same as Or. 42, half of folio 19r and the whole of the verso are blank, but there is no break in the text).</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="27v" to="65r"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Services for the second day of Rosh ha-Shanah</title>
							<note>
								<p>Shaḥarit, folio 27v; musaf, folio 46r (same as Or. 42).</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="65r" to="248r"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Services for Yom Kipur</title>
							<note>
								<p>Ma῾ariv, folio 65r (same as in Or. 42, folio 85r is blank); shaḥarit, folio 85v (piyutim are the same as in Or. 42, but the order of seliḥot is different); musaf, folio 155v; minḥah, folio 203r; ne῾ilah, folio 235r.</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="248r" to="309v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Services for Sukot</title>
							<note>
								<p>Ḳerovah for the first day of Sukot, folio 248r; yotser for the second day, folio 258v; yotser for mo῾ed de-Sukot, folio 266v; ma῾ariv for Shemini ῾atseret, folio 269r; yotser for Shemini ῾atseret, folio 271v; yotser for Simḥat Torah, folio 286v; hosha῾not, folio 294v; ma῾ariv for the first night, folio 304v; ma῾ariv for Shemini ῾atseret, folio 307r.</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
					</msContents>
					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment codex of the 13th to early 14th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<support>Parchment.</support>
								<extent>309 folios <dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>335</height>
										<width>250</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>200</height>
										<width>155</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>309 folios (+ 2 unfoliated paper flyleaves at the beginning and 3 at the end). Folio 1 is a paper flyleaf.</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>Quires of mostly 8 leaves each.</p>
									<p>Catchwords at the end of the quires, mostly cut away.</p>
								</collation>
								<condition>
									<p>Defective at the end.</p>
									<p>Stained.</p>
									<p>Folio 252 partly mutilated.</p>
								</condition>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="1 " ruledLines="21" writtenLines="20">
									<p>Uniform layout.</p>
									<p>Visible pricking and plummet ruling.</p>
									<p>Initial words written in larger characters. </p>
									<p>Hair side and flesh side hardly distinguishable.</p>
									<p>A vellum strip stiched to folio 210.</p>
									<p>A number of marginal notes and directions, in various hands.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="1">
							<summary>Ashkenazi square script, punctuated, of the 13th to early 14th century.</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="major"/>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>Folio 1 (a late paper flyleaf) contains an index of seliḥot for Yom Kipur.</p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="owner">Yitsḥaḳ ben Eli῾ezer ha-Kohen</name>: inscribed (folio 309v).</p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="owner">Matatyah ben Yuda</name>: inscribed (folio 309v); his name (Mataty' b"r Yudah Levi z"l) tooled on the contemporary 14th century binding.</p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p>Pre-1600. Black leather, blind-tooled, with copper centerpiece, cornerpieces and remains of clasps. Boxed.</p>
								<p>Spine: 'Mahazor. German Rite. Hebrew. Brit. Mus. Harley 5701.'</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
					</physDesc>
					<history rend="visible">
						<origin notBefore="1200" notAfter="1329"/>
						<provenance>
							<p>
								<name type="place">Germany</name>
							</p>
						</provenance>
						<acquisition>
							<date>1753</date>
							<p>The Harley Collection, formed by <name type="person" role="owner">Robert Harley</name> (b. 1661, d. 1724), 1st earl of Oxford and Mortimer, politician, and <name type="person" role="owner">Edward Harley</name> (b. 1689, d. 1741), 2nd earl of Oxford and Mortimer, book collector and patron of the arts[, inscribed as usual by their librarian, <name type="person">Humfrey Wanley</name>, ‘15 Augusti 1715’ (folio 2r).
Edward Harley bequeathed the library to his widow, <name type="person" role="owner">Henrietta Cavendish, née Holles</name> (b. 1694, d. 1755) during her lifetime and thereafter to their daughter, <name type="person" role="owner">Margaret Cavendish Bentinck</name> (b. 1715, d. 1785), duchess of Portland; the manuscripts were sold by the Countess and the Duchess in <date calendar="Gregorian">1753</date> to the nation for £10,000 (a fraction of their contemporary value) under the Act of Parliament that also established the British Museum; the Harley manuscripts form one of the foundation collections of the British Library.</p>
						</acquisition>
					</history>
